 it is probably from Clavering near Wooler (Northumb)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel Clavering was born in 1325, in Burgh, Norfolk, England, her father, Robert Clavering, was 51 and her mother, Margery de Clavering, was 21. She married John Mautby about 1356, in Paston, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1375, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1325–1375":"1325–1375","1345–1374":"1345–1374","1360–1398":"1360–1398","1275–Male":"1275–Surnud","1305–1325":"1305–1325","1374":"1374","1275":"1275","1360":"1360","aft 1325":"pärast 1325","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","1345":"1345","1453":"1453","1398":"1398","1375":"1375","about 1356":"umbes 1356","1328":"1328","Paston, Norfolk, England":"Paston, Norfolk, England","Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Burnham Thorpe, Norfolk, England","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Smallburgh, Norfolk, England":"Smallburgh, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Burgh St. Mary, Flegg, Norfolk, England":"Burgh, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1325–1375":"1325–1375","1345–1374":"1345–1374","